Imagine a very long webpage with many sections (i.e. an HTML specification on one page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), how about if the web server streams this section first and then the other sections?
Streaming order:
1. HTML document from start to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3 etc.
Dann would the browser make sure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed on the webpage over section 7.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements with JavaScript again. I simply want a longer HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. With HTML it should work.
The content could be streamed in, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
and so on.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it were streamed in order.
@user22 You can also reorder documents without JS like this. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to display first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) doesn't match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows non-sequential streaming, but the browser would then arrange the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 oh, do you want the browser to bring the DOM order into line?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, just so the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that could work without affecting the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would take care of making the resulting DOM order match the visual order.
So, Section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look like all sections have been streamed in sequence.
@user22 @user23 Look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
